					<description><![CDATA[<p>Britain Accelerates Quantum Ambition With £260M OQC Series C Round Oxford Quantum Circuits has raised £260 million in a Series C funding round led by Bullhound Capital. The round is</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/oqc-raises-260m-quantum-computing-series-c/" data-wpel-link="internal">Oxford Quantum Circuit Raises £260M Led by Bullhound Capital</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Britain Accelerates Quantum Ambition With £260M OQC Series C Round</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Oxford Quantum Circuits has raised £260 million in a Series C funding round led by Bullhound Capital. The round is the largest private quantum computing investment in Europe. It was oversubscribed with strong participation from global institutional investors and sovereign-linked capital groups. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Total funding for OQC now reaches approximately £430 million across three rounds. The investor base includes the British Business Bank, Fynveur, COFIDES, Alpha Edison, Fulcrum Asset Management, and Pentland Ventures. Oxford colleges and investment groups also participated, including Magdalen College Oxford and Oxford Capital. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Existing backers such as Oxford Science Enterprises and Chevron Technology Ventures returned to support the round. JPMorgan acted as exclusive placement agent on the transaction. The funding signals rising confidence in quantum computing as critical infrastructure. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">It also reflects increasing competition between the UK, US, Europe, and Asia in deep tech systems. Investors are backing companies capable of moving beyond lab-stage experimentation. OQC is positioned as one of the few firms already operating deployed quantum systems in commercial environments.</span></p>
<h2><b>Coaxmon Architecture Pushes Data-Centre Quantum Deployment</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">OQC builds superconducting quantum computers using its proprietary Coaxmon architecture. The system uses a 3D qubit design that reduces wiring complexity and improves stability. This approach is designed for integration into commercial data centres rather than isolated laboratories. It enables </span><a href="https://www.spinquanta.com/news-detail/quantum-hardware-explained-a-complete-guide" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">quantum hardware</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> to sit alongside AI and classical compute infrastructure.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company already operates systems across the UK, US, Japan, and Spain. One deployment includes New York City’s first quantum computer hosted in a Digital Realty facility. That system runs alongside high-performance AI hardware from Nvidia. OQC’s customers include financial institutions, defence organisations, and scientific research groups.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">CEO Gerald Mullally described the raise as a shift from long-term promise to near-term delivery. He said the company now has capital to scale internationally and improve system performance. Founder and Chief Scientific Officer Peter Leek emphasised engineering reliability and integration with trusted infrastructure. The focus remains on making quantum computing commercially usable at scale.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company’s model differs from competitors offering only cloud-based quantum access. OQC instead deploys physical systems directly into enterprise environments. This positions the company closer to infrastructure providers than software platforms. It also aligns quantum computing with existing data-centre investment cycles.</span></p>
<h2><b>Global Quantum Race Intensifies Across Competing Architectures</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Quantum computing remains a fragmented global technology race. Multiple hardware approaches are competing for long-term dominance. IBM and Google use superconducting qubits similar to OQC. Quantinuum focuses on trapped-ion systems backed by Honeywell. Pasqal develops neutral-atom architectures while PsiQuantum builds photonic systems.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Each approach offers different advantages in stability, scalability, and error correction. No consensus exists on which model will achieve fault-tolerant quantum computing first. Current systems remain in the noisy intermediate-scale phase. These machines are powerful but still limited in real-world commercial applications.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Despite technical constraints, investment is accelerating across the sector. Quantinuum has raised $600 million at a $10 billion valuation. PsiQuantum has secured more than $2.1 billion in total funding. Pasqal is preparing a Nasdaq listing, while IQM continues to expand European operations. Capital is flowing ahead of technical maturity.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">OQC is competing on infrastructure deployment speed rather than theoretical scale. The company is building installed systems in enterprise environments. This strategy aims to secure long-term customer integration before the market consolidates. The assumption is that deployment scale will shape future market leadership.</span></p>
<h2><b>UK Government Backs Quantum Sector With £2 Billion Commitment<br />
</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_202337" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202337" class="size-full wp-image-202337" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/create-a-futuristic-neon-lit-poster-with_101pc5x6XY2ysAV5n4bR5g_W0asR3bxTQqKSJMEgjhEcA_cover.png" alt="UK quantum computing strategy showing government-backed funding and private investment driving national infrastructure development." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-202337" class="wp-caption-text">The UK accelerates quantum computing as strategic infrastructure, aligning government funding and private capital to build global competitiveness. Source: Created by Ventureburn</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The UK government has increased its focus on quantum computing as strategic infrastructure. Chancellor Rachel Reeves confirmed up to £2 billion in funding support for the sector. This positions quantum technology alongside AI and advanced computing as national priorities. The goal is to secure global competitiveness in foundational technologies.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">OQC’s £260 million raise aligns with this broader industrial strategy. Government and private capital are now converging on quantum scale-up efforts. Bullhound Capital described OQC as a key player in global infrastructure transition. Barclays Chair Nigel Higgins said the company is building critical systems for enterprise adoption.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Oxford Science Enterprises highlighted OQC’s progression from research spinout to global platform. The funding round reinforces confidence in UK-origin deep tech scaling. It also signals growing international investor interest in British quantum companies. The UK is positioning itself as a hub for quantum infrastructure development.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Policy support is becoming a key driver of quantum investment. Governments are competing to host early-stage infrastructure providers. This includes funding, procurement access, and research partnerships. OQC benefits directly from this alignment between state strategy and private capital.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/wordsmith-raises-70m-legal-ai-platform/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Wordsmith Raises $70M to Rewire In-House Legal Work</span></a></p>
<h2><b>Infrastructure Race Builds Before Fault-Tolerant Era Arrives</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Quantum computing is still years away from full fault tolerance. Current systems suffer from high error rates and limited stability. However, companies are already building infrastructure ahead of that milestone. The strategy is to control deployment environments before the technology matures.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The race is increasingly about positioning rather than performance. Firms with early enterprise integration may dominate future markets. Data-centre presence is becoming a key competitive advantage. It allows companies to embed quantum systems into real workloads early.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">OQC is betting on this infrastructure-first model. Its systems are already deployed in multiple global regions. The company is focusing on integration, reliability, and scalability. Investors are backing the view that deployment scale will define future leadership.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The outcome remains uncertain. US and Chinese competitors have larger capital pools. Technical breakthroughs could still reshape the landscape. But early infrastructure control may prove decisive in commercialisation.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To stay updated on crypto venture capital funding and market trends, visit our </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/category/news/venture-capital/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">venture capital news section</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> for more insights.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/oqc-raises-260m-quantum-computing-series-c/" data-wpel-link="internal">Oxford Quantum Circuit Raises £260M Led by Bullhound Capital</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
