										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Building the Next Layer of Orbital Transportation</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Impulse Space has raised $500 million in Series D funding to accelerate its in-space mobility infrastructure. The round values the company at $4.26 billion. It brings total capital raised to more than $1 billion. Investors continue to back the company’s vision for post-launch orbital transport systems.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The funding marks a major milestone for the Redondo Beach-based aerospace company. Impulse Space is building </span><a href="https://www.britannica.com/technology/spacecraft" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">spacecraft</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> that move payloads after launch. These systems are designed to reposition satellites across different orbits. The company sees this as a critical missing layer in the space economy.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Impulse Space was founded in 2021 by Tom Mueller, a key propulsion engineer from SpaceX. The company focuses on in-space mobility rather than rocket launch. Its core idea is simple. Launch vehicles place satellites in orbit. But they do not take them where they need to go next.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company develops orbital transfer vehicles known as “space tugs.” Its flagship system, Mira, has already flown multiple missions. Mira performs precision manoeuvres and satellite positioning in orbit. It has also demonstrated autonomous docking and complex orbital operations.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Impulse is also developing Helios, a higher-energy transfer vehicle. Helios is designed to move payloads to geostationary and deep-space orbits. The system uses the company’s proprietary Deneb propulsion engine. First flight is expected in 2027. The goal is to reduce orbital transfer times from months to days.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company says demand for post-launch mobility is growing quickly. Satellites are increasingly deployed in complex orbital architectures. These include communications, defence, and Earth observation systems. Impulse aims to provide the infrastructure that connects launch to final deployment.</span></p>
<h2><b>Series D Capital to Scale Production and Infrastructure</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The $500 million Series D round was co-led by 137 Ventures and BANNER VC. Existing investors including Founders Fund, Lux Capital, and Linse Capital also participated. The company will use the capital to scale manufacturing and expand operations.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Impulse plans to increase production of its Mira and Helios spacecraft. It will also grow its engineering and mission operations teams. The company currently has over 200 open roles. Hiring will span propulsion, avionics, autonomy, and systems engineering.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Facilities are also expanding across multiple US locations. These include Redondo Beach, Boulder, Washington D.C., and Mojave. Each site supports different parts of design, testing, and manufacturing. The company has already more than doubled its workforce in the past year.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Leadership says the funding will allow faster execution at scale. Demand from commercial and government customers continues to grow. Impulse already holds hundreds of millions of dollars in contracts. The new capital will help deliver on that backlog.</span></p>
<h2><b>Demand Driven by a Shifting Space Economy<br />
</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_202282" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202282" class="size-full wp-image-202282" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/create-a-futuristic-neon-lit-poster-with_jknHkA1xWbaBQWie02V8TQ_1c-5MymOR4WjkFRQ6Ziyhw.png" alt="Orbital transport vehicles repositioning satellites along glowing paths with a deep-space craft heading to high-energy orbit" width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-202282" class="wp-caption-text">A new logistics layer in space enabling faster, smarter satellite deployment. Source: Created by Ventureburn</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The space industry is shifting beyond launch services. Rockets have become more reusable and cost-efficient. However, orbital logistics remains complex and expensive. Satellites often require long and inefficient transfer paths after deployment.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Impulse Space is targeting this gap in the value chain. Its vehicles act as orbital transport systems. They reposition satellites quickly and efficiently after launch. This reduces fuel consumption and extends satellite lifespan.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The Helios system is central to this strategy. It is designed to deliver payloads to high-energy orbits rapidly. This includes geostationary, lunar, and interplanetary trajectories. The company positions it as a same-day orbital delivery service.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The broader market is also evolving rapidly. Large satellite constellations are increasing demand for flexible deployment. Defence programmes are also expanding orbital requirements. These trends are creating a need for responsive in-space mobility infrastructure.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Impulse believes this mobility layer will become essential. It compares the concept to logistics networks on Earth. Rockets provide access to space. Orbital vehicles provide movement within it. The company is building systems to serve both commercial and government missions.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: <a href="https://ventureburn.com/newlimit-raises-435m-longevity-medicine-trials/" data-wpel-link="internal">NewLimit Raises $435M to Advance Longevity Medicine Trials</a></span></p>
<h2><b>Defence Growth and Long-Term Infrastructure Play</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Impulse Space is also gaining attention from defence programmes. The company has been working on space mobility systems with national security applications. These include rapid orbital manoeuvring and payload repositioning capabilities.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">It is also collaborating with defence partners on space-based systems. These efforts align with broader missile defence initiatives. Such programmes require fast and precise orbital control. Impulse’s propulsion systems are designed for this type of mission profile.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The defence sector offers long-term contract potential. It also provides stable revenue streams compared to commercial satellite markets. Analysts expect significant growth in space-based defence spending over the next decade.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company’s leadership sees this as part of a larger infrastructure buildout. Space is becoming a multi-layered economy. Launch is only the first step. Orbital movement and logistics are emerging as the next frontier.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Impulse Space now sits at the centre of that transition. With over $1 billion in funding and multiple missions already completed, the company is scaling rapidly. Investors are betting that in-space mobility will become foundational infrastructure for the future of space operations.</span></p>
